		<item>
		<title>Money and Values</title>
		<link>https://llgt.cafe/money-and-values</link>
					<comments>https://llgt.cafe/money-and-values#respond</comments>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[llgt]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Mon, 10 Apr 2023 14:35:18 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Faith]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Finances]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Money]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Spiritual]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Bible]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[LLGT]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://llgt.cafe/?p=703</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[Money and valuesDid you know that the Bible mentions money more than 800 times? Money does several things. It is a tool that allows us to do the things that we want to do, taking place of the barter system. But money also shows us&#160;<a class="read-more" href="https://llgt.cafe/money-and-values">&#8230;</a>]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<p>Money and values<br>Did you know that the Bible mentions money more than 800 times? Money does several things. It is a tool that allows us to do the things that we want to do, taking place of the barter system. But money also shows us what is important to us.</p>



<p>When we get paid, if we work for someone else, we pay a portion of our income to our government in the form of taxes. This amount varies in amounts and in percentages. Many of us get money back at the end of the year, while others winding up having to send in a check, but taxes always have to be paid.</p>



<p>Some people give away a percentage of their income. If you give a tenth of your income, to a church or some other charitable organization, it’s called a tithe. The Bible tells us that everything that we receive, whether we realize it or not, comes from God and that we should give a portion back to him. Some say that it should be 10 percent, but others say that it is “whatever God puts on your heart to give.” I admit that it’s not always easy to give, but it is always a good idea.</p>



<p>Next, one should “pay” him or herself. This means taking money and setting it aside for the future. It can be in the form of an emergency fund, a fun fund, or something to be used to build up investments that, hopefully, outdo inflation.</p>



<p>One of the most important things that a person needs to survive is shelter, so rent or a mortgage would come next. And, so you don’t loose your property at some point in the future, it’s a good idea to include taxes in the equation, if applicable.</p>



<p>Utilities come next, unless you want to be cold in the winter or hot in the summer. There’s also water and, if you like, telephone and internet. Cable would likely fall under entertainment.</p>



<p>It’s also a good idea to spend a portion of your income on food, unless you are the Dragon Warrior (from “Kung Fu Panda”). I know that a person can survive on about $20 US a month on Raman noodles, but that kind of diet isn’t going to lend to long term health, and peanut butter and jelly isn’t much better. How much you want to spend on food is up to you. Consider your overall budget and use your best judgment.</p>



<p>There are going to be other bills: petrol or travel, auto repairs or bus fair. Car insurgence may be one of the bills. You may think that you don’t need money for entertainment, but you likely will. And clothes wear out, so include it.</p>



<p>Debts should be a small part of what our money goes to. Unfortunately, credit card companies, who will give a credit card even to a dog, make it super easy to get into debt at a young age, and make it very hard to get out. In addition, the cost of education has gone through the roof and can make it hard to set any money aside at the time when we most need to start investing.</p>



<p>Finally, there are things. We all want things, but we have to consider what they are worth to us. Not only do “things” take away the money that we could give back to God, but they take away from the money that we can invest in ourselves and in our future. If we put our money in things, unless they are truly investments, we are putting money into things that won’t last, will need repair and that will need to be taken care of. It’s okay to have things, but not at the cost of our freedom.</p>



<p>A budget is a good way to track all of this spending. It can be as complicated as software that helps us track where our money is going, or as simple as a system using envelopes that hold cash for each category of spending. Whoever you spend your money shows what you really value. As Matthew 6:21 (KJV) puts it, “For where your treasure is, there will your heart be also.”</p>



<p>Where are your treasures? Do you put your money in things that will or will not last. It’s okay to have some of each but, remember, that balance is key. And the choices are up to you.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
					<wfw:commentRss>https://llgt.cafe/money-and-values/feed</wfw:commentRss>
			<slash:comments>0</slash:comments>
		
		
			</item>
		<item>
		<title>Key Ingredients to Financial Success</title>
		<link>https://llgt.cafe/key-ingredients-to-financial-success</link>
					<comments>https://llgt.cafe/key-ingredients-to-financial-success#respond</comments>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[llgt]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Sat, 18 Mar 2023 14:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Finances]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Money]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[LLGT]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://llgt.cafe/?p=605</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[In a way, finances is like baking. I’ve been baking long enough to know that baking bread just takes a few ingredients. Unlike the bread at the store that has a list of 20 to 30 ingredients, home made bread just has a few: flower,&#160;<a class="read-more" href="https://llgt.cafe/key-ingredients-to-financial-success">&#8230;</a>]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<p>In a way, finances is like baking. I’ve been baking long enough to know that baking bread just takes a few ingredients. Unlike the bread at the store that has a list of 20 to 30 ingredients, home made bread just has a few: flower, water, yeast or some other leavening agent, unless it’s kosher, along with a few other optional ingredients, and time in an oven or furnace.</p>



<p>When it comes to personal finances, what it boils down to is doing a few things right, over and over again over a long period of time. The better of a start that we can get, and the more consistent that we are over time, not acting in faith one moment and fear in the next, the better we are likely to be in the long run.</p>



<p>The first thing to do is to have a plan. Part of this is not only knowing where the money that comes in will go but also that there will be money left over. It means having an overall plan for one’s life so that there’s no spending on the things that won’t take you where you want to go. It means knowing yourself to realize that that fishing boat may not be the best purchase or that that trip to Hawaii can wait another year.</p>



<p>It means that, if you plan to start your own business, that you are willing to put in the effort and allow for the time that it can take to start a new business. It may seem like some people have been able to start making money right away but, if you listen to them, they will tell you that it took, in most cases, years before they were making the kind of money that they were making. Often, they are the ones making the money because everyone else gave up.</p>



<p>Yes, budgeting is part of the planning process, but even the best budget is no good if you don’t follow it. A budget is simply a road map for where you want to go. If you don’t know where you want to go, or if you don’t follow the map, it simply won’t work.</p>



<p>The second key is to spend less than you take in. It’s not enough to have credit available at the end of the month, you need to have real money that you can use if needed. This means planning not only for the monthly bills but for the unexpected: job loss, emergency expenses and alike.</p>



<p>Finally, you need to invest. These days, there are so many ways to invest, even if it’s just sweat equity, or working extra hard so that you have extra money. Whether it’s sweat equity or some other form of investing, if you fail to invest, you will either not make any progress or you will fall behind over time. You can start at any time, but the earlier that you start, the sooner that you will be able to get where you want to be.</p>



<p>The stock market has never been easier to get into than now. If you are to do well, however, you have to do your research. Otherwise, your investing odds are likely no better than at the casino. Housing can be a great area to invest, but it also requires a lot of work. You or someone that you hire have to collect rent and take care of the units/homes. Plus, you have to work with banks and sellers, getting not only the best price but the best interest rate. You have to be able to take risks with other people’s money and, if things take a turn for the worse, you could be responsible for repaying a whole lot of money.</p>



<p>You, yourself could be an investment. Education is just one form of investment. If used properly, an education could double the money that you would have otherwise made. Or, it could just leave you paying off a student loan for years. My initial student loan was just under $30 thousand, but I hear of people who have loans that are closer to $150 thousand. However, I also heard of someone who had a $90 thousand loan who was able to pay off his student loan in a matter of a few years, simply by working harder at finding better jobs.</p>



<p>You don’t need a bunch of head knowledge to do well financially. You do, however, need to do certain things and do them well. It begins with knowing where you are and where you want to go. Most importantly, it begins with you.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
